{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "19 — Bootstrapping: From balaur to a Running Companion",
  "description": "How the binary starts: the no-args desktop launcher, port selection, PocketBase wiring, the schema baseline, the Kronk engine hook, cron choreography, the FTS5 search sidecar, and dev seeding. By the end you will know every decision that happens between typing `balaur` and seeing the first chat prompt.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 53,
      "title": "19.1 — No-args launch: rewriting argv",
      "description": "```go\nif launch.IsLauncherInvocation(os.Args[1:]) {\n    if addr, alive := launch.RunningInstance(launch.DataDir()); alive {\n        _ = launch.OpenBrowser(\"http://\" + addr + \"/\") // already running: open it, exit\n        return\n    }\n    isFirstRun = launch.IsFirstRun(launch.DataDir())\n    port, err := launch.SelectPort()\n    addr := fmt.Sprintf(\"127.0.0.1:%d\", port)\n    _ = launch.WriteInstanceLock(launch.DataDir(), addr)\n    os.Args = append(os.Args[:1], \"serve\", \"--http\", addr, \"--dir\", launch.DataDir())\n    go launch.OpenAfterReady(addr)\n}\n```\n\nA bare `balaur` with no subcommand or flags is the **desktop-launcher path**: pick a port, build a loopback address, and — critically — **rewrite `os.Args` into a normal `serve …` invocation before `pocketbase.New()`**. The rewrite must happen first because `--dir` is an eager flag that PocketBase parses at construction time.\n\nThe safety rule is total: `IsLauncherInvocation` returns true only when `len(args) == 0`. Any argument — a subcommand, a flag, even `-h` — puts the launcher in hands-off mode. Every existing path (explicit `serve`, Makefile binds, CLI verbs) is untouched.\n\nTwo later additions frame the rewrite. `launch.RunningInstance` (plan 232) is the **single-instance guard**: it reads the instance lock file and TCP-probes the recorded address; if a live instance answers, this second bare launch opens it in the browser and exits. It is FAIL-OPEN — any error, or a stale lock whose probe gets no answer, means proceed to a normal start. `launch.IsFirstRun` (plans 193/230) now feeds the **first-run onboarding banner**: the flag is stashed in `app.Store()` under `balaur_first_run` at OnServe, and the home handler renders a dismissible model-setup banner on a fresh box — it never gates the browser-open, which happens on every no-args boot.\n\nSee `internal/launch/launch.go` for the helpers; **Tour 00** (step 0.2) has a concise summary."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/launch/launch.go",
      "line": 83,
      "title": "19.2 — Port selection: stable default, loopback only",
      "description": "```go\nconst DefaultPort = 8099\n\nfunc SelectPort() (int, error) {\n    l, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", fmt.Sprintf(\"127.0.0.1:%d\", DefaultPort))\n    if err == nil {\n        l.Close()\n        return DefaultPort, nil\n    }\n    return FreeLoopbackPort()\n}\n```\n\n`DefaultPort` (8099) is a **stable bookmark**: the URL `http://127.0.0.1:8099/` does not change between boots as long as the port is free, making it bookmarkable for a non-developer owner. It sits in Balaur's 808x/809x family but avoids the two documented dev binds (8080 for `make run`, 8090 for `make dev`) so a normal dev box never collides.\n\n`SelectPort` probes the default by binding it and closing immediately. On any bind error (port already in use, permission denied) it falls back to `FreeLoopbackPort`, which asks the kernel for any free port via `127.0.0.1:0`.\n\nEvery address the launcher ever produces is `127.0.0.1:…` — **the package never constructs a non-loopback address** (stated in the package doc comment). This is a deliberate local-first constraint: AGENTS.md says Balaur is a loopback-first service, not exposed to the network without an explicit threat model.\n\nThere is a small TOCTOU window between probing the port and `serve` re-binding it; this is documented and accepted for a localhost launcher."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 97,
      "title": "19.3 — Wiring phases: New, migrations, CLI, OnServe",
      "description": "```go\napp := pocketbase.New()\nmigratecmd.MustRegister(app, app.RootCmd, migratecmd.Config{Automigrate: false})\ncli.Register(app, app.RootCmd)\napp.OnServe().BindFunc(func(se *core.ServeEvent) error {\n    se.App.Store().Set(\"balaur_first_run\", isFirstRun)\n    registerKronkEngine(se.App)\n    web.Register(se)\n    registerRecap(se.App)\n    registerNudge(se.App)\n    registerBriefing(se.App)\n    registerSearchIndex(se.App)\n    knowledge.RegisterCacheInvalidation(se.App)\n    ...\n})\napp.Start()\n```\n\n`main.go` has one job: **orchestration, not logic**. Four wiring phases in strict order:\n\n1. **`pocketbase.New()`** — creates the PocketBase app with SQLite storage. This is where `--dir` and `--http` are consumed, which is why the argv rewrite must precede it.\n2. **`migratecmd.MustRegister`** — enables `balaur migrate up/down/…`. `Automigrate: false` means migrations only run when explicitly triggered or at `serve` start; they never fire speculatively.\n3. **`cli.Register`** — mounts the machine-facing JSON gateway (`balaur chat`, `balaur task`, …) as subcommands. Same internal packages as the web UI; only the rendering differs.\n4. **`OnServe` hook** — everything that needs a live, migrated database: the Kronk engine, the web gateway, all three cron jobs, the FTS5 index, and the graph-link hooks. These are **lazy**: they run after migrations complete and the HTTP listener is up, never before.\n\nAGENTS.md invariant: *focused entry point — `main.go` stays thin; reusable or testable logic lives in `internal/*` packages.*"
    },
    {
      "file": "migrations/1749600000_init.go",
      "line": 34,
      "title": "19.4 — Schema baseline: InitCollections",
      "description": "```go\nfunc InitCollections(app core.App) error {\n    // heads, conversations, messages, nodes, edges,\n    // audit_log, summaries, tasks, entries, extensions,\n    // llm_providers, llm_models, llm_settings, owner_settings\n}\n```\n\n`InitCollections` is the **consolidated schema baseline** (plan 156): one Up function that creates all 14 core collections from scratch, replacing the pre-launch migration archaeology. The filename prefix `1749600000` is a Unix timestamp; PocketBase runs migrations in filename order, so the timestamp guarantees correct sequence.\n\nThe `init()` function above it registers the migration with PocketBase's runner — it fires automatically when the `migrations` package is imported (via the blank import `_ \"balaur/migrations\"` in `main.go`), before `main()` runs.\n\nAll collections carry `ruleOwner` API rules: direct REST access is limited to the authenticated owner. Collections written only by trusted Go code (`audit_log`, `summaries`) expose only List/View to the owner — their writes bypass rules via `app.Save`, which is documented Go-side behavior, not a security gap (AGENTS.md: *Go-side record access bypasses API rules by design*).\n\nLater migration files fold domain entities into the unified node spine (`1750000020_tasks_to_nodes`, `1750000030_measures_to_nodes`, …). **Tour 14** covers the resulting nodes collection and graph in depth."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 151,
      "title": "19.5 — The Kronk engine hook: lazy, no boot cost",
      "description": "```go\nfunc registerKronkEngine(app core.App) {\n    app.Store().Set(kronk.StoreKey, kronk.NewEngine(kronk.LibRoot(), turn.ResolveProcessor(app)))\n}\n```\n\n`registerKronkEngine` is the first call inside `OnServe`. It creates the in-process Kronk inference engine and stores it on `app.Store()` under `kronk.StoreKey` — where `internal/turn` will find it later when resolving the active `llm.Client`.\n\n**Nothing loads at this point.** `NewEngine` allocates the struct and records the runtime library directory and processor choice (`cpu` or `vulkan`). The native llama.cpp library is only dlopen'd on the first inference call; no model is loaded at boot. A box with no installed runtime and no GGUF model file starts cleanly.\n\n`turn.ResolveProcessor` picks the variant: the owner's saved choice from the Models page wins; absent that, `BALAUR_PROCESSOR` or the `cpu` default. If the chosen non-cpu variant's `.so` is not installed, it degrades to `cpu` rather than bricking the engine (fail-safe documented in the comment).\n\nThe paired `OnTerminate` hook (line 126) calls `eng.Close` to unload the resident models on shutdown.\n\n**Tour 11** covers the full Kronk engine lifecycle — init, streaming, model download, and runtime install."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 161,
      "title": "19.6 — Cron choreography: single-flight and catch-up",
      "description": "```go\nfunc scheduleJob(app core.App, name, spec string, tolerateNoModel bool, body func(client llm.Client)) {\n    var mu sync.Mutex\n    clients := turn.ClientSource{Engine: kronk.FromStore(app)}\n    run := func() {\n        if !mu.TryLock() { return } // skip if previous tick still running\n        defer mu.Unlock()\n        client, err := clients.Active(app)\n        ...\n        body(client)\n    }\n    app.Cron().MustAdd(name, spec, run)\n    go run() // serve-start catch-up\n}\n```\n\n`scheduleJob` is the single helper that wires all three background jobs (recap, nudge, briefing). Two patterns are baked in:\n\n**Single-flight:** `mu.TryLock()` ensures a slow run never overlaps the next tick. If the previous invocation is still in progress, the current tick is silently skipped.\n\n**Serve-start catch-up:** `go run()` fires immediately after registration, off the serve path. This matters for self-hosted boxes that sleep through the scheduled hour: on wake, recap runs within seconds rather than waiting for the next cron tick.\n\n**Owner-tz timing** is applied by each job body: recap and briefing call `store.OwnerLocation(app)` to convert the system clock to the owner's timezone before doing period math. `tolerateNoModel` controls whether a missing model is a hard skip (`recap`, which needs a real model call) or runs with a `nil` client (`nudge`, `briefing`, which can produce deterministic output without one).\n\nEach job is a hard env kill switch: `BALAUR_RECAP=0`, `BALAUR_NUDGE=0`, `BALAUR_BRIEFING=0` skip registration entirely (for nudge this sits above a soft, owner-driven mute layer in `owner_settings`). **Tour 13** covers the recap, nudge, and briefing domain logic."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 251,
      "title": "19.7 — The search sidecar: FTS5 on boot, hooks for freshness",
      "description": "```go\nfunc registerSearchIndex(app core.App) {\n    dbPath := filepath.Join(app.DataDir(), \"search.db\")\n    ix, err := openAndRebuild()\n    if err != nil {\n        os.Remove(dbPath)\n        ix, err = openAndRebuild() // one retry\n    }\n    app.Store().Set(search.StoreKey, ix)\n    app.OnRecordAfterCreateSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(upsertHook)\n    app.OnRecordAfterUpdateSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(upsertHook)\n    app.OnRecordAfterDeleteSuccess(\"nodes\").BindFunc(deleteHook)\n}\n```\n\nBalaur runs two SQLite engines by design: PocketBase's `modernc.org/sqlite` pure-Go driver for the main database, and `ncruces/go-sqlite3` (wazero) for the rebuildable FTS5 search sidecar at `pb_data/search.db`. FTS5 is needed for recall; it is not available in the primary driver. Both stay CGO-free — this is a deliberate cost, not drift.\n\nOn every boot: open the sidecar, call `Rebuild` to re-index all active nodes, and store the result on `app.Store()` under `search.StoreKey`. If open or rebuild fails (corrupt file, schema mismatch) the file is deleted and one retry is attempted. If the retry also fails, Balaur **boots without the index** — recall falls back to a SQLite `LIKE` search, keeping the app functional. A warning is logged but the boot never aborts.\n\nThree PocketBase record hooks keep the index eventually consistent between full rebuilds: upsert on create/update, delete on record delete — all scoped to the `nodes` collection.\n\n**Tour 09** covers the search package internals and the FTS5 recall path."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/seed/seed.go",
      "line": 70,
      "title": "19.8 — Dev seeding: idempotent, reversible, offline",
      "description": "```go\nconst Marker = \"seed\"\n\nfunc Run(app core.App) (*Result, error) { ... }\nfunc Reset(app core.App) (*Result, error) { ... }\n```\n\n`internal/seed` populates a Balaur box with realistic dummy data for testing and demos. It writes through the same domain packages the product uses (`conversation`, `tasks`, `knowledge`, `life`, `heads`) so the seeded box behaves exactly like a lived-in one — recaps, task buckets, life series, and the knowledge lifecycle all light up. **No model is called**: the package is deterministic and offline.\n\nThe design pivots on `Marker = \"seed\"` — every seeded record carries this tag in a real collection field (`messages.origin`, node `props.source`, `entries.value`, or a fixed natural key for collections without a spare field). This makes seeding:\n\n- **Idempotent:** `Run` checks for the marker before inserting; a second call without a `Reset` between adds nothing.\n- **Reversible:** `Reset` deletes only Marker-tagged rows and the fixed seed natural keys; real records are untouched.\n\n`Reset` uses `app.FindRecordsByFilter` + `app.Delete` per collection — straightforward Go-side PocketBase access, no raw SQL. The `Result` struct reports counts per collection so the caller (`balaur seed` CLI command) can print a human-readable summary.\n\n**Dev boxes are always seeded; prod boxes stay schema-only** (AGENTS.md memory note). On a reset, seed first, back up both data dirs before resetting."
    }
  ]
}
